# **Conservations Areas**
Rossendale currently has 10 Conservation Areas, designated under the Planning (Listed Buildings and Conservation Areas) Act 1990 and defined as "areas of special architectural or historic interest, the character or appearance of which it is desirable to preserve or enhance."
The reasons for designation vary widely but all Conservation Areas have in common historic and architectural features which make them worthy of additional protection

**The Council controls dangerous buildings under Sections 77 and 78 of the Building Act 1984.**
We respond to all reports of dangerous buildings, walls and structures within the borough on a 24 hour 365 day a year basis.
If a structure presents a potential danger to the safety of people, we will take action to remove the danger. We have legal powers to require the owners of buildings or structures to remedy the defects

**Brownfield Land Registers are presented in two parts****.**
Part 1 provides a comprehensive list of all sites in Rossendale that are suitable for housing and meet the criteria set out in the Regulations.
Part 2 is a subset of Part 1 of the Register and comprises sites which the Council considers could, in principle, be suitable for residential development. Sites entered into Part 2 of the Register are granted 'Permission in Principle'

  * Conservation of fuel and power
  * Access and facilities for those with disabilities

LABC Surveyors are able to help with problems beyond the scope of Building Control.
We respond to all reports of dangerous buildings, walls and structures within the Borough on a 24 hour 365 day a year basis.
For practical advice on home improvements, you can visit [LABC's Front Door website](https://labcfrontdoor.co.uk/). You can also download and view the Government's [guide to the Building Regulations](https://www.rossendale.gov.uk/download/downloads/id/16784/guide_to_building_regs.pdf).
